.TH LSAUDIO 1 "2026-06-07" "lsaudio 1.0.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
lsaudio \- list the processes that are currently playing or recording audio
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B lsaudio
.RB [ \-a ]
.RB [ \-j | \-p ]
.RB [ \-w ]
.RB [ \-\-no\-color ]
.RI [ pattern ]
.br
.B lsaudio kill
.RB [ \-s
.IR signal ]
.RB [ \-f ]
.RB [ \-n ]
.RB [ \-a ]
.RB [ \-\-no\-input ]
.RI [ target ]
.br
.B lsaudio
.B \-\-version
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B lsaudio
enumerates every client process registered with
.BR coreaudiod (8)
via the CoreAudio process object API (macOS 14+) and shows which of them are
currently playing or recording audio, together with their PID, bundle ID, and
the audio devices in use.
.PP
By default only active processes are listed. With
.BR \-a " / " \-\-all ,
every registered audio client is shown and idle ones are dimmed.
An optional
.I pattern
restricts the list to processes whose name or bundle ID contains the given
text (case-insensitive).
.PP
Note that browsers and Electron apps play audio from a helper process
(e.g.\&
.IR com.apple.WebKit.GPU
for Safari), not from the main application process.
.B lsaudio
shows the process that actually holds the audio session.
.SH LIST OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-a ", " \-\-all
Show every process registered with coreaudiod, including idle ones.
.TP
.BR \-j ", " \-\-json
Output JSON.
.TP
.BR \-p ", " \-\-plain
Output plain tab-separated text. This is also the automatic behavior when
stdout is not a terminal.
.TP
.BR \-w ", " \-\-watch
Watch for changes. On a terminal, the table is redrawn whenever audio
activity changes; when piped (or combined with
.BR \-\-plain ),
one tab-separated event line is emitted per change
.RI ( present ,
.IR start ,
.IR change ,
.IR stop ).
This mode is event-driven via CoreAudio property listeners; no polling takes
place.
.TP
.B \-\-no\-color
Disable colored output. The
.B NO_COLOR
environment variable and
.B TERM=dumb
are honored as well.
.SH KILL
.B lsaudio kill
sends a signal to audio processes matching
.IR target ,
which may be a PID, a bundle ID, or a case-insensitive name substring.
By default only
.I active
audio processes are matched, so a stray
.BR afplay (1)
can be ended without hitting idle audio clients. A confirmation prompt is
shown before any signal is sent.
.PP
Without a
.IR target ,
every active audio process is matched \(em
.B lsaudio kill
simply makes the noise stop. Combining this with
.B \-\-all
is refused, since it would signal every registered audio client, including
system daemons.
.TP
.BR \-s ", " \-\-signal " " \fIsignal\fR
Signal to send, as name or number (default: TERM). Supported names: CONT,
HUP, INT, KILL, QUIT, STOP, TERM, USR1, USR2.
.TP
.BR \-f ", " \-\-force
Skip the confirmation prompt.
.TP
.BR \-n ", " \-\-dry\-run
Only show what would be signalled.
.TP
.B \-\-no\-input
Never prompt; fail instead. Useful for scripts.
.TP
.BR \-a ", " \-\-all
Match among all registered audio processes, not only active ones.
.TP
.B \-\-sudo
Escalate via
.BR sudo (8)
when a target process belongs to another user (e.g. the root-owned
.IR systemsoundserverd ).
Without this flag, an interactive
.RB \(lq "Retry with sudo?" \(rq
prompt is offered when permission is denied. sudo performs its own
authentication; combined with
.BR \-\-no\-input ,
.B sudo \-n
is used so that nothing ever waits for a password.
.SH EXIT STATUS
.B lsaudio kill
exits with 0 on success, 1 if nothing matched, 2 if the operation was aborted
or confirmation was impossible, and 3 if a signal could not be delivered.
.B lsaudio --watch
exits with 130 on Ctrl-C.
.SH EXAMPLES
.TP
List processes currently playing or recording audio:
.B lsaudio
.TP
Live view of audio activity:
.B lsaudio --watch
.TP
Log audio start/stop events to a file:
.B lsaudio --watch --plain >> audio-activity.log
.TP
End a stray afplay left behind by a careless agent:
.B lsaudio kill afplay
.TP
Force-kill whatever Safari is playing:
.B lsaudio kill -s KILL -f WebKit.GPU
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR kill (1),
.BR afplay (1),
.BR coreaudiod (8)
.SH AUTHOR
Dr. Michael Lauer <mickey@vanille.de>
